				Greed seems rather the wrong word to me. Greed implies money or wealth. This is more an abuse of an obvious coding mistake. <br>  <br> It was not the intention of the game for you to be able to get to 126+ by clicking on a statue.  It was cute with Shadowclaim but that was so us Solclaimers didn't have the only high level characters - it also was mitigated to some extent since the result was a lot of high level chars with starting spells and sub-par equipment (couldn't afford scrolls or equipment).   <br>  <br> Characters on their home server will have good equipment and appropriate spells so getting more xp = getting more powerful and unkillable. <br>  <br> Players having lots of money is simply annoying for the game designers.  They just invent money sinks and let the in-game economy handle it.  However there is no &quot;xp sink&quot; you can spend xp on in the game and the economy can't make xp less useful, because you don't use xp for anything else except to become more powerful. Xp in essense is *used* not *spent*; your character will always benefit from xp you've spent (or you can simply untrain the offending skill and respend the xp if you don't get benefit from it). <br>  <br> It would have been worse if the xp could be passed up because the problem would multiply to other characters but since it's the paw, there is no passup.  It may be only that we have to thank for that we don't have a all server rollback. <br> 
						<p><span class="SignatureTitle">-----signature-----</span>
						<div class="SignatureText">
						Tomoe Ohara, Lvl 102 Spec Bow 3 School, MelD <br> Tarithwen Ohara, Lvl 55 Spear me the Details w/Lockpick <br> Alconi bint-Malconi, Lvl 30 Og Mageling <br> 9/11/01 <img src="/images/faces/sad.gif" border=0 alt="sad.gif" height=16 hspace=0 width=18 vspace=0>  <br> 
						</div>
							

